INSERT INTO prompts (prompt_type, name, description, prompt_text, is_active, opportunity, agency, created_by) SELECT 'source-list', 'Trial Lawyer + Insurance News - Colorado', 'Source List: Trial Lawyer + Insurance News (Colorado)', 'We want to push the need for insurance reform in Colorado:
Your task is to collect around 2-5 relevant links based on the topic provided. Focus on non-news-outlet websites and X (Twitter) posts that discuss the topic with a similar narrative or angle.
Output format (strict)
Provide two lists only, in this order:
List A: X (Twitter) posts
List B: Website links (non-news outlets only)
No summaries. No commentary. Links only, one per line.
List A: X (Twitter) posts — STRICT identity of person/organization + credibility gate
Do not include random users. If identity/affiliation cannot be confidently verified from the profile itself, exclude it.
Step 1: Collect candidates
Find posts that match the topic’s narrative/angle, prioritizing recency and relevance.
Step 2: Validate the account (mandatory)
Only include a post if the author account passes ALL checks below:
A) Account type must be one of these
Real individual (named human) with over 3000 followers, OR
Official organization (company/NGO/institute/government body/university/think tank), OR
Recognized public figure (politician, academic, executive, journalist, notable author) clearly labeled as such.
B) Identity must be explicit on-profile (hard requirement)
The profile must contain ALL of the following, visible in the profile (display name + bio + profile image):
Clear real name OR official organization name
Individuals: first + last name required (no single-name IDs).
Orgs: clearly official brand/org name (not a generic theme page).
Role/title (e.g., “Professor”, “Policy Director”, “CEO”, “Researcher”, “Partner”, “Analyst”, “MP”, etc.)
Organization / institution / employer (company, university, think tank, NGO, government body, lab, fund, etc.)
Profile image that matches the identity type
Individuals: headshot-style photo
Orgs: logo/official brand mark
If any of these are missing, exclude the account.
C) External verifiability signal (must have at least ONE)
At least one of:
Verified badge (any verification type), OR
Official website link in profile that matches the name/org, OR
Work email domain in bio/linked site that matches the org, OR
Explicit institutional marker in bio (e.g., “@Company”, “at University X”, “Director at Y”) that is specific and checkable.
If none are present, exclude.
D) Hard exclusions (no exceptions)
Exclude accounts that are:
Anonymous/pseudonymous, parody, meme, fan, “commentary”, “aggregator”, “alerts”, “clips”, “daily ____”, “insider”, “patriot”, “truth”, etc.
Pages that “look official” but don’t state exact org identity + role markers.
Individuals with only vague descriptors (“writer”, “commentator”, “entrepreneur”, “investor”) without employer/institution.
Accounts where the name appears fake (random strings, handles presented as names, no surname for individuals).
Any account where you cannot confidently answer: Who is this, what is their job/title, and where do they work?
E) Diversity + volume requirement (to avoid being too narrow)
To maximize output while staying credible:
Include a mix of: academics, analysts, executives, policy professionals, reputable NGOs/think tanks, regulators, and official company accounts.
Prefer multiple posts per credible account rather than adding borderline accounts.
List A output rule: link directly to the post only (e.g., https://x.com//status/), one per line, newest → oldest.
List B: Website links (non-news outlets only)
Prioritize organizations and credible expert pages, such as:
Think tanks, institutes, universities, labs
NGOs, policy groups, regulators, standards bodies
Company blogs/research hubs/whitepapers/technical notes
Expert personal sites only if the author is clearly identified with credentials + institutional affiliation
Exclusions for List B
Exclude:
News outlets (newspapers, magazines, broadcasters)
Scraped sites, link farms, anonymous blogs, and forum threads as primary sources
List B output rule: links only, one per line, newest → oldest.
Ordering + recency (both lists)
Recency is a priority.
Order each list newest → oldest.
If publish dates aren’t visible, use best available signals (page “Updated” date, post timestamp).
Goal
Produce highly relevant links that are credible and attributable (real people or official organizations), maximizing relevance + recency + credibility, while never including unverifiable accounts.', true, 'Trial Lawyer + Insurance News', 'Trial Lawyer + Insurance News', 'spreadsheet-import' WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM prompts WHERE name = 'Trial Lawyer + Insurance News - Colorado' AND prompt_type = 'source-list');
